        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The word so rendered occurs first in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 16:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where it is directed that the pot of manna is to be laid up before the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Testimony",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". That by this is meant some portion of the Law which was given to Moses is made clear in a later passage. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 25:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 25:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is described as ‘the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Testimony",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " which I shall give thee’. We need not suppose that in these passages the whole law of Moses is intended, but the name given to the first portion of the Law would no doubt be continued in after times for all that was considered to be the divine revelation. Hence we must here understand the Law, as the people then possessed it. Express direction is given in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:18-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that when a king shall be chosen he shall have a copy of the Law, which he shall study ‘that he may learn to fear the Lord his God, to keep all the words of this law and these statutes to do them’. So the delivery of the Law would naturally form a most solemn portion of the coronation ceremony.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
