            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and anointed him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] This was not done as far as we know with all kings, but the present was a special occasion, and no part of the ordinance would be omitted which could help to mark in a religious manner the restoration of the true scion of David’s house.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and they clapt their hands",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] A natural expression of approval and applause, though not frequently spoken of in the O. Test. It is found in the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 47:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of exultation before God, and the figure is used ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 98:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘Let the floods clap their hands’. But it is quite as frequently used where rejoicing over a fallen enemy is the cause (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 27:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Lamentations 2:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nahum 3:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "God save the king",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Literally ‘Let the king live’. So they cried when Saul was made king, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 10:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and at the feast of Adonijah when he sought to be king, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 12.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Jehoiada - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "brought forth the king's son",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - produced him, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from the chamber or chambers where he had been concealed hitherto. (On the temple chambers, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 13:4-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And put the crown upon him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " That the Israelite kings actually wore crowns appears from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 1:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 20:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The crown was probably a band of gold, either plain or set with jewels (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Zechariah 9:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), fastened behind with a riband. It receives here the same name that is given to the high priest's diadem in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 29:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and Exodus 39:30. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And gave him the testimony.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The words \"gave him\" are not in the original, and are superfluous. What is meant plainly is that the high priest laid on the young king's head a copy of the Law, or of some essential portion of it, perhaps the Decalogue, which is often called \"the testimony\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 16:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 25:16, 21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). The object apparently was to show that the king was to rule by law, not arbitrarily - that he was to be, as Dean Stanley says, \"not above, but beneath, the law of his country\" ('Jewish Church,' vol. 2. p. 397). The ceremony seems to have been a new one, and is indicative of the gradual curtailment of the regal power under the later monarchy. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And they made him king, and anointed him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " A change is made from the singular to the plural, because, as we learn from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 23:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"Jehoiada ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and his",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " sons anointed him.\" We have had no mention of the anointing of a new monarch in Judah since the time of Solomon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It may, however, have been the usual practice. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And they",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the people - all who were present - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "clapped their hands",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - an ordinary sign of joy (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 47:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 98:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Isaiah 4:12; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nahum 3:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.) - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and said, God save the king!",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "long live the king",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "! (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 10:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 16:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:25, 39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). 2 Kings 11:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "After the approaches to the temple had all been occupied in this manner, Jehoiada brought out the king's son from his home in the temple; or, he brought him forth, set the crown upon him, and handed him the testimony, i.e., the book of the law, as the rule of his life and action as king, according to the precept in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:18-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ואת־העדוּת is connected with את־הנּזר עליו יתּן, because עליו יתּן has the general meaning \"delivered to him, handed him,\" and does not specially affirm the putting on of the crown. ימליכוּ, they made him king. The subject is the persons present, through, as a matter of course, the anointing was performed by Jehoiada and the priests, as the Chronicles expressly affirm. Clapping the hands was a sign of joyful acclamation, like the cry, \"Long live the king\" (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]